flavorText: It tends to move in a pack with others. They cluster in a tight group to sleep in a cave.
Bathed in the setting sun of evening, Lycanroc has undergone a special kind of evolution. An intense fighting spirit underlies its calmness.
Shaped like an ancient writing, it is a huge mystery whether language or Unown came first.
This legendary Pokémon is said to represent the land. It went to sleep after dueling Kyogre.
Beware of pushing strongly on its squishy body, as it makes a mysterious purple fluid ooze out.
Tempered by pressure underground over tens of thousands of years, its body cannot be scratched.
A mysterious Pokémon. Some say it is a lifeform from another dimension, while others believe it is formed from smog.
This Pokémon came to the defense of Pokémon that had lost their homes in a war among humans.
They say that it stays still and quiet because it is seeing both the past and future at the same time.
Half of all blackouts occur when this Pokémon appears at power plants and eats electricity.
If it rampages, it knocks down mountains and buries rivers. Maps must be redrawn afterward.
While seeking iron for food, it digs tunnels by breaking through bedrock with its steel horns.
Brave and prideful, this Pokémon dashes airily through the forest, its steps aided by the psychic power stored in the fur on its fetlocks.
It lives in burrows dug on sandy beaches. Its pincers fully grow back if they are broken in battle.
It claws if displeased and purrs when affectionate. Its fickleness if very popular among some.
By flapping its leafy fan, it can whip up gusts of 100 feet per second that can level houses.
When Reshiram's tail flares, the heat energy moves the atmosphere and changes the world's weather.
When the horns on its head shine in seven different colors, it is said to be sharing everlasting life.
Bisharp pursues prey in the company of a large group of Pawniard. Then Bisharp finishes off the prey.
It sends out electromagnetic waves, which let it float through the air. Touching it while it's eating electricity will give you a full-body shock.
It makes an inescapable conical pit and lies in wait at the bottom for prey to come tumbling down.
It lies still in the same pose for days in its web, waiting for its unsuspecting prey to wander close.
It is said to be the guardian of the seas. It is rumored to have been seen on the night of a storm.
With strengthened bodies, they skillfully wield steel beams to take down buildings.
They awaken at dusk and take wing in the twilight, leading to the expression, "Get home before the Murkrow fly."
In Alola, Komala is Hypno's main target. It rarely harms people.
Lacking sight, it's unaware of its surroundings, so it bumps into things and eats anything that moves.
Its tail discharges electricity into the ground, protecting it from getting shocked.
It rubs its snout on the ground to find and dig up food. It sometimes discovers hot springs.
If its body takes on an aura, the weather changes instantly. It is said to live in seas and lakes.
Legends say it can share eternal life. It slept for a thousand years in the form of a tree before its revival.
It is said that happiness will come to those who see a gathering of Clefairy dancing under a full moon.
It lives on snowy mountains. Having had little contact with humans, it is boldly inquisitive.
The weakest Dragon-type Pokémon, it lives in damp, shady places, so its body doesn't dry out.
Interlocking two bodies and spinning around generates the energy they need to live.
Its fluffy coat swells to double when static electricity builds up. Touching it can be shocking.
Spinning minigears are rotated at high speed and repeatedly fired away. It is dangerous if the gears don't return.
Its round face and smooth coat—softer than the most high-class velvet—have made this a very popular Pokémon in Alola.
After it has eaten up all the food in its territory, it moves to another area. Its two heads do not get along.
Artillery platforms built into the walls of ancient castles served as perches from which Golurk could fire energy beams.
Shaped like an ancient writing, it is a huge mystery whether language or Unown came first.
This rough Pokémon stores energy inside its body, then sweeps across the land, shooting off electricity.
Born from gases, anyone would faint if engulfed by its gaseous body, which contains poison.
They flock in great numbers. Though small, they flap their wings with great power.
This legendary Pokémon battled against humans to protect Pokémon. Its personality is calm and composed.
Although small, its venomous barbs make this Pokémon dangerous. The female has smaller horns.
No matter where in the world it goes, it knows where its nest is, so it never gets separated from its Trainer.
It faces strong opponents with great courage. But, when at a disadvantage in a fight, this intelligent Pokémon flees.
The melodies sung by Meloetta have the power to make Pokémon that hear them happy or sad.
The curved antlers subtly change the flow of air to create a strange space where reality is distorted.
When Honedge evolves, it divides into two swords, which cooperate via telepathy to coordinate attacks and slash their enemies to ribbons.
A mysterious life-form called an Ultra Beast. Witnesses saw it pulverize a dump truck with a single punch.
They form groups of roughly 20 individuals. Their mutual bond is remarkable—they will never let down a comrade.
It is said to deliver happiness. Being compassionate, it shares its eggs with injured people.
It can instantly create many diamonds by compressing the carbon in the air between its hands.
It swims elegantly by flittering its tail as if it were a dress. It has the look of a queen.
Beware of pushing strongly on its squishy body, as it makes a mysterious purple fluid ooze out.
The bone it holds is its key weapon. It throws the bone skillfully like a boomerang to KO targets.
It doggedly pursues its prey wherever it goes. However, the chase is abandoned at sunrise.
A single cry from this nocturnal Pokémon, and more than a hundred of its Murkrow cronies will assemble.
Spinning minigears are rotated at high speed and repeatedly fired away. It is dangerous if the gears don't return.
A plan was recently announced to gather many Pikachu and make an electric power plant.
It is said to make its home somewhere in the sea. It guides crews of shipwrecks to shore.
Strong impacts can knock it out of its shell. This Pokémon was born from mutated nanoparticles.
It was born when sludge in a dirty stream was exposed to the moon's X-rays. It appears among filth.
It drifts aimlessly in waves. Very difficult to see in water, it may not be noticed until it stings.
It is said that happiness will come to those who see a gathering of Clefairy dancing under a full moon.
It is very small and powerless. If attacked, the best it can do is flap its leaves in an attempt to frighten away its enemies.
Because it turns active on nights of the full moon, it is said to have some link to the lunar phases.
When it finds a stone of a suitable size, it secretes a liquid from its mouth to open up a hole to crawl into.
A Pokémon that startles people in the middle of the night. It gathers fear as its energy.
It has the ability to distort space. It is described as a deity in Sinnoh-region mythology.
It has about three times the electrical power of Magnemite. For some reason, outbreaks of this Pokémon happen when lots of sunspots appear.
Watch your step when wandering areas oceans once covered. What looks like a stone could be this Pokémon, and it will curse you if you kick it.
Its thin, balloon-like body is inflated by horribly toxic gases. It reeks when it is nearby.
They cannot see, so they tackle and bite to learn about their surroundings. Their bodies are covered in wounds.
Found in fields and mountains. Mistaking them for boulders, people often step or trip on them.
It drives away opponents by excreting a sticky liquid that can dissolve anything. Its eyes devolved, so it can't see anything.
Males have plumage on their heads. They will never let themselves fell close to anyone other than their Trainers.
If one of the twin Koffing inflates, the other one deflates. It constantly mixes its poisonous gases.
It always stands on one foot. Even when attacked, it does not brace itself using both feet.
Since their two heads do not get along and compete with each other for food, they always eat too much.
Its shell is overflowing with its heightened otherworldly energy. The ectoplasm serves as protection for this Pokémon's core spirit.
A Pokémon with a loyal nature. It will remain motionless until it is given an order by its Trainer.
It responds to movement by attacking. This scary, three-headed Pokémon devours everything in its path!
Anyone who dares peer into its body to see its spectral ball of fire will have their spirit stolen away.
Concealing itself in lightning clouds, it flies throughout the Unova region. It creates electricity in its tail.
When its boulder is broken in battles for territory, it feels unsure and begins to weaken.
Its constant mischief and misdeeds resulted in it being bound to an Odd Keystone by a mysterious spell.
Although it always pretends to be a tree, its composition appears to be closer to a rock than a plant.
It moves with its sensitive nose pressed to the ground, always searching for food.
It freely controls three small units called Mini-Noses using magnetic force.
Shaped like ancient writing, it is a huge mystery whether language or Unown came first.
Appears in filthy areas. Thrives by sucking up polluted sludge that is pumped out of factories.
The gear with the red core is rotated at high speed for a rapid energy charge.
It has a very tenacious nature. Its acute sense of smell lets it chase a chosen prey without ever losing track.
Generations of kings were attended by these Pokémon, which used their spectral power to manipulate and control people and Pokémon.
When endangered, it may protect itself by raising its magnetism and drawing iron objects to its body.
As it zooms through the sky, this Pokémon seems to be receiving signals of unknown origin, while transmitting signals of unknown purpose.
It uses the leaf on its head to determine the temperature and humidity. It loves to sunbathe.
If it senses danger, it scares the foe by crying out with the volume of a jet-plane engine.
The long hair around its face provides an amazing radar that lets it sense subtle changes in its surroundings.
This very friendly Dragon-type Pokémon will hug its beloved Trainer, leaving that Trainer covered in sticky slime.
It's a fiend for gemstones, so it stalks Carbink. Unfortunately, Gabite almost always grabs them first.
It lives in caves on the seafloor and creates giant whirlpools every time it moves.
A rare Pokémon discovered during a deep-sea exploration. It has not changed in over 100 million years.
Its upper whiskers are sensors that survey its surroundings. Its lower whiskers are organs that shoot electricity.
A Pokémon created by recombining Mew's genes. It's said to have the most savage heart among Pokémon.
Its tongue is made of gas. If licked, its victim starts shaking constantly until death eventually comes.
To protect itself, it afflicts those around it with nightmares. However, it means no harm.
It charges ahead and bashes its opponents like a berserker, uncaring about any hits it might take. Its arms are mighty enough to snap a telephone pole.
A pair may be seen rubbing their cheek pouches together in an effort to share stored electricity.
Poison oozes from all over its body. It catches and eats small bugs at night that are attracted by light.
Stiffens its ears to sense danger. The larger, more powerful of its horns secretes venom.
Its cheeks hold poison sacs. It tries to catch foes off guard to jab them with toxic fingers.
Long ago, superstitions were spread about it, saying it brought disaster. This fed a hatred of it, and it was driven deep into the mountains.
Generations of kings were attended by these Pokémon, which used their spectral power to manipulate and control people and Pokémon.
Males have plumage on their heads. They will never let themselves feel close to anyone other than their Trainers.
As it grows, the stone portions of its body harden to become similar to a diamond, though colored black.
On the night of a full moon, if shadows move on their own and laugh, it must be Gengar's doing.
Its highly developed jaws are powerful enough to crush anything. Even experienced adult trainers must handle it with great caution.
A poor walker, it often falls down. However, its strong pride makes it puff up its chest without a care.
With its incisors, it gnaws through doors and infiltrates people's homes. Then, with a twitch of its whiskers, it steals whatever food it finds.
It has the power to control time. It appears in Sinnoh-region myths as an ancient deity.
It loyally follows its Trainer's orders. For ages, they have helped Trainers raise Pokémon.
It enshrouds itself with sand to protect itself from germs. It does not enjoy getting wet.
